column168: WHILE LOADING BAGS OF PRODUCT STACKED ON PALLETS, USING A PALLET JACK, ONE PALLET WAS SET IN PLACE ON LEFT SIDE OF CARGO COMPARTMENT.  SECOND PALLET WAS THEN LOADED ON THE TRUCK.  APPARENTLY ONE CORNER OF THE WOOD PALLET PUNCTURED THE SIDE OF BOTTOM BAG ON THE FIRST PALLET.  THE PUNCTURE WAS SMALL, BUT GRADUALLY PRODUCT TRICKLED OUT.  THE EMPLOYEE DID NOT REALIZE A BAG WAS PUNCTURED DUE TO THE FACT THE PUNCTURE WAS SMALL, THE SPILLED PRODUCT GRADUALLY TRICKLED OUT, BUT MOST IMPORTANTLY, THE SECOND PALLET SET IN POSITION BLOCKED THE VISION OF THIS UNINTENTIONAL RELEASE OF PRODUCT FROM ITS PACKAGE.  THE RELEASE WAS DISCOVERED WHEN THE VEHICLE BECAME DISABLED AND WAS BEING OFF-LOADED.  APPROXIMATELY 1 - 2 POUNDS OF MATERIAL WAS RELEASED FROM THE PACKAGE.  THE DOT WAS PRESENT WHEN THE DISABLED VEHICLE WAS BEING OFF-LOADED.  THE OFFICERS PRESENT THOROUGHLY INVESTIGATED THE SITUATION AND DETERMINED THE SPILL WAS NOT THE RESULT OF A PACKAGE FAIULRE, BUT INCIDENTAL PUNCTURE.
BACKED INTO TELEPHONE POLE.  BENT UNLOADING HEADER ON TRAILER.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS TRAVELING NORTHBOUND ON HWY 87 15 MILES SOUTH OF GRASS RANGE, MT WHEN AN APPARENT ELECTRICAL FIRE OCCURRED IN THE TRACTORS DASH. THE DRIVER PULLED THE TRACTOR-TRAILER TO THE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD AND EXHAUSTED 3 FIRE EXTINGUISHERS IN AN ATTEMPT TO CONTROL THE FIRE.  THE DRIVER COULD NOT GET THE FIRE UNDER CONTROL AND THE ENTIRE TRACTOR-TRAILER AND CARGO WAS TOTALLY DESTROYED.  INCLUDED IN THE CARGO OF THE TRAILER, WAS 64 LBS. OF ENGINE STARTING FLUID.  THIS STARTING STARTING FLUID WAS RELEASED AS A RESULT OF THE FIRE, WHICH DESTROYED ALL CONTENTS IN TRAILER.

WITH ASSISTANCE FROM THE SPRINGBORO FIRE COMPANY, THE DRIVER CLOSED THE PACKING NUT HAD LOOSENED WHICH ALLOWED THE VALVE TO VIBRATE OPEN. ALL PERSONNEL HAVE BEEN INFORMED OF THE INCIDENT AND INSTRUCTED ON PROPER LOADING PROCEDURES TO PREVENT RECURRENCE OF THIS TYPE OF INCIDENT.

ON OCTOBER 3, 1995, AN ASSOCIATED COURIERS, INC., STRAIGHT TRUCK LEFT THE ACI WAREHOUSE IN LEMONT, ILLINOIS, ENROUTE TO AMERSHAM/MEDI+PHYSICS, INC., IN ALRLINGTON HEIGHTS, ILLINOIS. AT APPROXIMATELY 1:00 P.M. CENTRAL TIME, THE TRUCK WAS NORTHBOUND ON LEMONT ROAD CROSSING THE BRIDGE OVER THE DES PLAINES RIVER WHEN THE REAR DOOR CAME OPEN AND A PACKAGE CONTAINING RADIOACTIVE MATERIALS FELL ONTO THE ROADWAY. THE DRIVER RETRACED HIS ROUTE AND FOUND THE PACKAGE IN ONE OF THE NORTHBOUND LANES ON THE BRIDGE. IT HAD BEEN RUN OVER BY ONE OR MORE VEHICLES WHICH CAUSED SEVERE DAMAGE TO THE PACKAGE RESULTING IN THE RELEASE OF THE RADIOACTIVE CONTENTS. RESPONDING TO THE EVENT WERE REPRESENTATIVES OF THE LEMONT POLICE AND FIRE DEPARTMENTS, THE ARGONNE NATIONAL LABORATORIES' EMERGENCY RESPONSE UNIT, ASSOCIATED COURIERS, INC., AMERSHAM/MEDI+PHYSICS, INC., THE DEPARTMENT OF ENERGY AND THE ILLINOIS DEPARTMENT OF NUCLEAR SAFETY. EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL CLOSED BOTH THE NORTHBOUND AND SOUTHBOUND LANES WHILE THEY WERE SURVEYED AND CHARACTERIZED. THE UNCONTAMINATED SOUTHBOUND LANES WERE REOPENED AT 4:50 P.M. RADIOACTIVE MATERIALS REMOVED FROM THE NORTHBOUND LANES WERE GIVEN TO AMERSHAM FOR DISPOSITION. AFTER DECONTAMINATION, THE NORTHBOUND LANES WERE REOPENED AT 5:30 P.M. THE ACI DRIVER WAS CITED FOR IMPROPER BLOCKING AND BRACING. HE HAS BEEN SUSPENDED FOR FAILURE TO FOLLOW STANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURES UNTIL A DECISION IS MADE REGARDING HIS FUTURE EMPLOYMENT WITH ACI.

THE YARD CONTACTED THE CONSIGNEE, MADISON INDUSTRIES, BUT THEY REFUSED TO RESPOND.  FORTUNATELY, CHEMTREC WAS ABLE TO REACH THE SHIPPER, STD. CHLORINE, AFTER SOME DIFFICULTY, AND THEY DISPATCHED A TEAM.  THE TEAM ARRIVED AT 0115 HOURS, REPLACED A RUPTURED FRANGIBLE DISC AND GASKET AND RETURNED THE CAR TO US AT 0230.  THE VERY SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT ON THE TOP OF THE CAR WAS NEUTRALIZED AND REMOVED BY THE STD. CHLORINE TEAM.

ANDES CHEMICAL COMPANY WAS LOADING THEIR FREIGHT ONTO OUR TRAILER WITH A FORKLIFT WHEN THEY PUNCTURED THE DRUM WHICH WAS LOADED IN FRONT OF THEIR SHIPMENT. CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED AT THE TIME OF THE OCCURENCE.  WE RECEIVED HANDLING INSTRUCTIONS FROM ELF ATOCHEM AND RETURN AUTHORIZATION FROM MR. HUGH MCLAUGHLIN.

AN INDIVIDUAL WAS INJURED AFTER COMING IN CONTACT WITH A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DURING THE LOADING OF A TRANSPORT VEHICLE SPLASHED INTO THE INDIVIDUAL'S EYES.  AFTER RECEIVING IMMEDIATE FIRST AID, THE INDIVIDUAL WAS TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL AND ADMITTED.

NO FURTHER LEAKAGE WAS OBSERVED.  ABSORBANT MATERIAL WAS PLACED ON SPILLED LIQUID.  THIS WAS TAKEN AND DISPOSED OF AT THE TSDF.  NO FURTHER PROBLEMS WERE ENCOUNTERED.

WHILE LOADING SHIPMENT, DRIVER BECAME CONCERNED ABOUT THE QUALITY AND INTEGRITY OF THE CONTAINERS GOING ON BOARD.  FURTHER INSPECTION REVALED SIX (6) CONTAINERS LEAKING THROUGH THE SIDEWALL OF THE PACKAGE.  THE ENTIRE SHIPMENT WAS REJECTED AND OFF-LOADED.  THE TRAILER FLOOR WAS CLEANED WITH ABSORBANT MATERIAL WHICH WAS LEFT WITH THE SHIPPER.  THE TRUCK WAS NOT RELOADED.

column168: THE DRIVER WAS EN ROUTE ON I-75 SOUTH TO TIFTON, GA.  AS THE VEHICLE PASSED THE 213 MILEMARKER NEAR EXIT 69, EYEWITNESS ACCOUNTS AND TIRE TRACKS CONFIRM THAT THE VEHICLE GRADUALLY LEFT THE ROADWAY ONTO THE SHOULDER, GRADUALLY BEARING SLIGHTLY TO THE RIGHT INTO THICK TREES BORDERING THE HIGHWAY.  THE INITIAL IMPACT WITH THE TREES CAUSED A FIRE AND SEVERE DAMAGE TO THE POWER UNIT.  THE IMPACT RUPTURED THE FUEL TANKS AND THE DIESEL FUEL IGNITED, ENGULFING THE TRACTOR IN FLAMES.  THE TRAILER SEPARATED FROM THE TRACTOR AND LAND ON ITS SIDE.  THE OUTSIDE SHELL OF THE TRAILER RECEIVED EXTENSIVE DAMAGE, INCLUDING NUMEROUS PUNCTURES, CRACKS, AND TEARS.  THE ANNULAR SPACE LOST ITS VACCUUM, HOWEVER,THE INNER VESSEL REMAINED INTACT.  NO PRODUCT WAS LOST AS A RESULT OF THE IMPACT. DURING RECOVERY OPERATIONS, APCI EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL ATTEMPTED TO TRANSFER THE PRODUCT TO ANOTHER CARGO TRAILER BUT WERE SUCCESSFUL.  TO REDUCE THE PRESSURE HAZARD, PERMISSION WAS GRANTED AT THE SCENE TO VENT THE PRODUCT TO ATMOSPHERE BEFORE ATTEMPTING TO REMOVE THE TRAILER.  AS A RESULT OF THE ACCIDENT, THE DRIVER WAS FATALLY INJURED.  PRELIMINARY INVESTIGATIONS BY COUNTY POLICE INDICATES THAT OUR DRIVER BECAME INCAPACITATED PRIOR TO LEAVING THE ROADWAY.  A HEART ATTACK IS SUSPECTED PENDING FINAL MEDICAL EVALUATION.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: WHILE IN THE PROCESS OF UNLOADING GATX 36728, WORKERS AT THE CITY OF RICHMOND WATER PURIFICATION PLANT DISCOVERED THAT THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE OF THE TANK CAR LEAKING.  THE WATER PLANT WORKERS PLACED THE CHLORINE "C" KIT OVER THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE, BUT, WERE UNSUCCESSFUL IN COMPLETELY STOPPING THE LEAK.  IN THE PROCESS OF INVESTIGATING AND CONTAINING THE LEAK, THREE (3) EMPLOYEES OF THE WATER PLANT WERE OVERCOME FROM EXPOSURE TO CHLORINE.  THE THREE EMPLOYEES WERE TRANSPORTED TO A LOCAL HOSPITAL FOR TREATMENT AND OBSERVATION.  THEY WERE RELEASED FROM THE HOSPITAL WITHIN FOUR (4) HOURS.  THE CITY OF RICHMOND BUREAU OF FIRE RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND ATTEMPTED TO FURTHER SLOW THE LEAK BY ADJUSTING THE CHLORINE KIT HOOD ASSEMBLY.  THEY TOO WERE UNABLE TO FULLY STOP THE LEAK. THE CHLOREP TEAM FROM OCCIDENTAL CHEMICAL, DELAWARE CITY, DE, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  THE CHLOREP TEAM FROM OCCIDENTAL CHEMICAL, DELAWARE CITY, DE, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  THE CHLOREP TEAM WAS ABLE TO FULLY SEAL OFF THE LEAK UTILIZING THE CHLORINE "C" KIT. THE LEAK WAS SEALED AT 0800 HOURS ON 10/22/95. THE TANK CAR GATX 36728WAS AND HAD BEEN PLACED ON THE CITY OF RICHMOND SIDING FOR SIX (6) DAYS AND WASIN THE CUSTODY OF THE CITY OF RICHMOND.  CSX TRANSPORTATION IS FORWARDING THISREPORT DUE TO THE COMPANY'S KNOWLEDGE OF THE INCIDENT. CSXT WAS NOT INPOSSESSION OF THE CAR AT THE TIME OF THE RELEASE.

column168: DRIVER NOTICED LIQUID COMING FROM VAN.  HE IMMEDIATELY PULLED ON TO THE SHOULDER OF THE HIGHWAY.  DRIVER CALLED IN AND REPORTED THE INCIDENT. CHEMPLY INITIATED OUR OFF-SITE EMERGENCY RESPONSE PLANT.  FOR UNKNOWN REASONS THE FITTING/VALVE FELL OFF THE PORTABLE TANK.  THE PORTABLE TANK WAS SECURE IN BACK OF THE VAN ALL OTHER MATERIAL WAS AT LEAST FOUR FT. AWAY, NOTHING STRUCK THE TANK.  NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO COUNTY AND STATE EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT, NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER PA DEP.  CLEANUP WAS DONE BY A RESPONSE CONTRACTOR - WEAVERTOWN ENVIRONMENTAL GROUP.

AFTER THE DRIVER MADE HIS HOOKUP TO THE CONSIGNEE'S VAPOR AND DISCHARGE HOSES, HE STARTED PUMPING AND DISCOVERED THAT THEIR DISCHARGE LINE WAS EMITTING VAPOR.  DRIVER SHUT OFF PUMP AND LET PRODUCT DRAIN BACK INTO TANK AND CLEANED OFF CONNECTION WITH STEAM.  HE DISCOVERED THAT THE GASKET BETWEEN HOSE AND TRAILER FITTING HAD SLIPPED.  DRIVER REINSTALLED GASKET AND UNLOADED TANK TRAILER.

PUT #2 FUEL OIL SPILLER IN COMPARTMENT ON TOP OF TRAILER & PULLED HANDLE TO LOAD PRODUCT.  NOTICED METER WAS NOT RUNNING AND AT THE SAME TIME, NOTICED #4 OIL BEING RELEASED FROM #4 SPILLER NOT ATTACHED TO TRAILER. SHUT DOWN RACK, CONTAINED SPILL, AND BEGAN CLEAN-UP WITH SORBENT BAGS AND SORBENT PADS.  TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENT, DRIVERS WILL NOT LOAD FROM THAT BAY, AS BAY IS CONGESTED WITH MULTIPLE PRODUCTS FROM WHICH TO LOAD.

AT APPROXIMATELY 0835 HOURS ON OCTOBER 11, A CAR INSPECTOR NOTICED AN ODOR EMANATING FROM TANK CAR GATX 19010.  ALLENTOWN FIRE DEPARTMENT AND LA ROCHE INDUSTRIES RESPONDED AND DISCOVERED THE ANGLE VALVE AND PACKING GLAND NUT NOT FULLY SECURED.  THEY TIGHTENED SAME AND OKED CAR TO DESTINATION.

WHEN TRAILER DOOR WAS OPENED FLOOR WAS WET AND FUMES DETECTED.  TRAILER WAS ALLOWED TO AIR OUT & OIL DRY WAS PUT ON FLOOR TO CLEAN UP SPILLAGE. WHEN DRUM WAS FOUND ON TRAILER A SMALL PUNCTURE WAS DETECTED IN THE MIDDLE OF THE DRUM.  SIZE OF PUNCTURE WAS APPROX. THE DIAMETER OF A DIME.  VERY LITTLE  PRODUCT LOST.  AT MOST 5 GALLONS.  DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY PUT INTO A RECOVERY DRUM.  TRAILER WAS SWEPT OUT AND OIL DRY PUT IN DUMPSTER.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM OSRAM SYLVANIA, INC. LOCATED AT 0900 TYRONE PIKE IN VERSAILLES, KY TO CLEAN HARBORS OF NATICK, INC. LOCATED AT 10 MERCER ROAD IN NATICK, MA.  DURING A ROUTINE STOP AT SPRING GROVE RESOURCE RECOVERY, INC. LOCATED AT 4879 SPRING GROVE AVENUE IN CINCINNATI, OH IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 1 PINT OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM THE TOP CHIME OF ONE OF THE CONTAINERS ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE, ABSORBED ALL FREE LIUQIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY AND PLACED THE LEAKING CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM. column62: Defective Component or Device; Corrosion - Exterior
column168: THE DRIVER PULLED OVER ON THE EDGE OF PURCHASE PARKWAY AT THE FULTON, KENTUCKY, EXIT NO. 2 (MILE MARKER 2) FOR A TIRE CHECK WHEN HE NOTICED HYDROCHLORIC ACID LEAKING FROM THE REAR OF TRAILER 30805.  THE DRIVER NOTIFIED OUT FACLITY IN HENDERSON, KENTUCKY, OF THE PROBLEM.  PB&S CHEMICAL COMPANY EMERGENCY RESPONSE EMPLOYEES FROM OUT PADUCAH, KENTUCKY, FACILITY ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AND PROCEDED TO ENTER THE VAN TRAILER TO DETERMINE THE TYP OF LEAK AND WHICH CONTAINER WAS LEAKING.  AFTER DETERMINING THAT PORTABLE TANK NO. 180462 WAS LEAKING FROM THE VALVE AREA, A DECISION WAS MADE TO TRANSFER THE CONTENTS INTO OTHER CONTAINERS.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND THE AREA WAS CLEANED UP.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES. UPON RECEIVING PORTABLE TANK NO. 180462 BACK INTO OUR HENDERSON FACILITY, AN INVESTIGATION BEGAN TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE OF THE FAILURE.  THE VALVE VALVE CONNECTION AND POLY CONTAINER BODY WERE EXAMINED.  THE CONCLUSION FROM THIS INVESTIGATION WAS THAT WE HAD A FAILURE OF THE VALVE CONNECTION, GASKET AND THE VALVE BOLTS.  THE BOLTS HAD CORRODED WHICH ALLOWED THE SEPARARION OF THE VALVE BODY FROM THE POLY CONTAINE BODY.

THE DRIVER CONTAINED THE SPILL WITH A SPILL RESPONSE KIT. THE TRAILER WAS RINSED AND THE RINSE CONTAINED AND DRUMMED FOR DISPOSAL VIA STABILIZATION AT THE DISPOSAL SYSTEMS, INC. FACILITY IN DEER PARK, TX. THE LOUISIANE DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY, LOUISIANA STATE TROOPERS, AND NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (REPORT 311143) WERE NOTIFIED OF THIS DISCHARGE.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: ON OCTOBER 17, 1995 AT 11:30AM, A TRACTOR-TRAILER OPERATED BY RESOURCES TRANSPORTATION SERVICES (RTS) WAS BEING UNLOADED INTO A CUSTOMER'S TANK. AS THE UNLOADING FINISHED, THE UNLOADING HOSE CAME LOOSE SPILLING APPROXIMATELY 0-15 GALLONS OF A DILUTE (^15%) CAUSTIC SODA SOLUTION ONTO THE CONTAINMENT AREA.  THE SPILL WAS WASHED DOWN AND LOADED INTO A VACUM TRUCK; THE RECOVERED WASTE WAS THEN DISPOSAL AT THE DISPOSAL SYSTEMS, INC. DEEPWELL INJECTION FACILITY IN DEER PARK.  TEXAS.

column168: WASTE FLAMMABLE LIQUID MIXTURE BEING TRANSPORTED FOR DISPOSAL WERE PACKAGED IN 5-GALLON POLY PAILS AND LOADED WITH OTHER HAZARDOUS MASTES. SERVERLA PAILS WERE STACKED ON PALLETS AND SHRINK WRAPPED TOGETHER FOR SHIPMENT.  DURING THE COURSE OF NORMAL TRANSPORTATION, THE LOAD SHIFTED DUE TO INADEQUATE BRACIN AND SEVERAL PAILS TOPPLED OFF THE APLLET ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR.  THREE OF THE INVERTED PAILS BEGAN TO LEAK.  UPON NOTICING THE LIQUIDS DRIPPING FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER, THE DRIVER PULLED TO THE SIDE OF THE ROAD AND PLACED A BUCKET BENEATH THE TRAILER TO COLLECT THE LIQUIDS.  ALL RESULTANT SPILLED MATERIAL (2-GALLONS) WAS REMEDIATED AND THE LEAKING CONTAINERS UPRIGHTED.  OPERATIONS TRAINING FOR PROPER BRACING OF LOADS GIVEN TO DRIVERS.

DURING UNLOADING ACTIVITIES A 55 GALLON CONTAINING CRESYLIC ACID WAS INADVERTENTLY PUNCTURED WITH THE DRUM HANDLING EQUIPMENT (I.E., DRUM GRABBER).  LEAKING DRUM WAS PROPMTLY OVERPACKED.  SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED AND REMOVED FROM THE TRAILER FLOOR AND SURRONDING PAVED AREA. AS A PREVENTIVE MEASURE, ADDITIONAL SAFETY TRAINING WILL BE GIVEN REGARDING THE OPERATION OF DRUM HANDLING EQUIPMENT.

A SET OF TRAILERS ARRIVED AT YARD FROM HOUSTON. A STRONG ODOR WAS COMING FROM THE REAR TRAILER AND WAS REPORTED TO ME BY MECHANIC. WE WENT TO CHECK OUT THE TRAILER AND NOTHING WAS LEAKING OUT OF THE TRAILER BUT IT DID HAVE A STRONG SMELL LIKE NATURAL GAS COMING FROM THE TRAILER. THE OPERATION MANAGER AND MYSELF WENT BACK TO OFFICE TO CHECK THE LOAD MANIFEST TO SEE WHAT WAS ON THAT TRAILER. WE FOUND THAT THERE WAS 1 EA. 5 GALLON PAIL OF FLAMMABLE LIQUID N.O.S. WHICH CONTAINED (BUTYL MERCAPTAN AND PROPYL MERCAPTANS, 3, UN1993, PGII.) WHICH IS USED TO MIX WITH NATURAL GAS TO GIVE IT AN ODOR. WE WENT BACK AND OPENED TRAILER AND FOUND THAT A PALLET OF TIRES HAD SHIFTED AND SMASHED THE PAIL PUNCTURING THE SIDE, CAUSING CONTENTS TO LEAK OUT. THE LIQUID HAD EVAPORATED BY THE TIME WE OPENED THE TRAILER. WE HAVE PICTURES OF THE INCIDENT ON FILE. ORIGIN TERMINAL WILL BE NOTIFIED AND SHIPPER ALSO.

column168: SHIPMENT WAS ENROUTE BETWEEN MEMPHIS, TN AND LEXINGTON, KY ON A ROAD TRAILER. THE ROAD DRIVER STOPPED FOR A TIRE CHECK AT THE 92 MILE MARKER OF THE WESTERN KY PARKWAY AT CANEYVILLE, KY. HE NOTICED SOME LIQUID LEAKING OUT THE BACK DOOR OF THE TRAILER. HE OPENED THE TRAILER DOOR AND FOUND THE DRUM TO BE LEAKING ABOUT HALFWAY UP ON THE DRUM. HE MANEUVERED THE DRUM TO A POINT WHERE IT STOPPED LEAKING. AFTER THE DRUM WAS SECURE THE DRIVER CALLED THE COMPANY BREAKDOWN CENTER AND REPORTED THE INCIDENT. PERSONNEL AT THE BREAKDOWN CENTER NOTIFIED AN ENVIRONMENTAL CLEAN-UP CONTRACTOR CALLED EVERGREEN WHO CAME AND CLEANED UP THE SPILL. THE DRIVER STATED THAT THE DRUM LOOKED LIKE IT WAS IN BAD CONDITION (BATTERED). SHIPPERS SHOULD CHECK CONTAINERS TO ENSURE THAT THEY ARE WORTHY FOR TRANSPORT BEFORE SHIPPING.

Q 20 FT CONTAINER ON A FLAT CAR WAS FOUND LEAKING AT CSX INTERMODEL'S FACILITY IN SAVANNAH, GA .  SHIPPER, STATE FEDERAL AND LOCAL AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED.  CSX RESPONDED A CLEAN UP CONTRACTR OUT OF JACKSONVILLE, FL.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZ MAT TEAM DIRECTED THE CONTAINER TO BE GROUNDED AND OPENED.  THE F.D HAZ MAT TEAM WITH ASSISTANCE FROM CSX PERSONNEL UNLOADED THE CONTAINER AND FOUND ONE LEAKING DRUM.  THE DRUM WAS LEAKING FROM A CREASE/GOUGE NEAR THE BOTTOM.  THE F.D. PLACED THE DRUM IN AN OVERPACK.  THE CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR NEUTRALIZED THE SPILLED MATERIAL ON THE FLAT CAR AND ON THE CONTAINER FLOOR, THEN RELOADED THE DRUMS, TO WAIT FOR THE SHIPPER DISPOSITION.  THE FIRD DEPT LEFT THE FACILITY AT APPROXIMATELY 1830 HOURS.

column168: DURING SAFETY CHECK, DRIVER DISCOVERED THAT ONE DRUM INSIDE THE TRAILER WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM.  DRIVER REMOVED THE DRUM, ABSORBED THE SPILLED MATERIAL AND OVERPACKED ALL WASTE.  ALL MATERIAL INCLUDING THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS THEN TRANSPORTED TO THE RECEIVER FOR DISPOSAL.  CAUSE OF THE SPILL APPEARED TO BE FROM A PINHOLE ON THE BOTTOM.

WHILE UNLOADING HEATING OIL INTO 1000 UNDERGROUND TANK, THE PRESSURE HOSE ON THE DIESEL PUMP SOMEHOW DEVELOPED A PINHOLE.  TE PUMPIN SYSTEM WAS SHUT DOWN IMMEDIATELY.  SINCE I WAS UNLOADING FROM A 580 GALLON TANK-A METER READING WAS TAKEN (143 GAL. UNLEADED SO FAR) I FLUSHED THE GAS PUMP WITH DIESEL FUEL FROM ANOTHER TANK THEN CONTAINUED PUMPING DIESEL FROM THE GAS SIDE-FINISHED UNLOADING 580 TANK & TOOK METER READING FROM GAS PUMP (437 GAL) & 14 GAL. FROM DIESEIL METER = 580 GAL. SO IN MY ESTIMATE THE VERY MOST PRODUCT LOSS COULD BE 3 GALLON.  SINCE IT HAD BEEN RAINING FOR 2 DAYS THE GROUND IN THE AREA OF THE SPILL WAS COMPLETELY SATURATED WITH RAINWATER, SUBSEQUENTLY NONE OF THE SPILL GOT INTO THE GROUND IT ALL FLOATED ON TOP ANS WAS RECOVERED USING ABSORBANT PADS TRUCK WAS RETURNED TO OROFINO TERMINAL & CLEANED & ABSORBANT PADS PROPERLY DISPOSED OF. ALL OF SPILLED PRODUCT RECOVERED.

column168: DRIVER WAS NORTHBOUND ON US 85.  WEATHER CONDITIONS DETERIORATED REAPIDLE, WIND WAS BLOWING AND IT WAS SNOWING.  VISABILITY WAS EXTREMELY POOR. DRIVER DRIFTED OFF THE ROAD ON THE RIGHT SIDE.  HE FELT THE EHICLE START TO GO OFF THE ROAD.  HE TRIED TO STEER IT INTO THE BARROW PIT RATHER THAN JERK IT BACK ONTO THE ROAD.  INSTEAD OF A BORROW PIT HE WENT OFF THE ROAD ON APPROXIMATELY A 20 FOOT FILL AREA.  THE UNIT ROLLED 3/4 TIME AND ENDED UP LAYING ON THE DRIVER'S SIDE AT THE BOTTOM OF THE FILL. column168: DRIVER WAS UNLOADING TANK TRAILER BY DRUMMING LOAD INTO SIX FOOT TOTES USING 80' OF HOSE WHILE ON A LADDER.  DRIVER WAS  HOLDING HOSE UP AT AN ANGLE AND DUE TO LOOSE OR FAULTY CONNECTION TO DRUMMING NOZZLE A SMALL AMOUNT WAS LEAKING DOWN HIS GLOVE AND INTO THE SLEEVE OF HIS SAFETY SUIT WHICH THEN TANK DOWN HIS ARM AND ONTO HI CHEST, CAUSING A BURN.  THE DRIVER WAS TREATED AT THE SITE AND LOCALLY AFTER HIS RETURN.  IN ORDER TO CORRECT THIS PROBLEM BOTH LABTECH AND GENERAL MOTORS HAVE AGREED TO HAVE AN EMPLOYEE TO ASSIST DURING THE UNLOADING.  ALL DRIVERS HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED TO BE SURE THAT LLA FITTING CONNECTIONS ARE TIGHT AND LEAK FREE AND AS AN ASSED PRECAUSTION TO TUCK THEIR SAFETY SUIT SLEEVES INTO THEIR GLOVES.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS EASTBOUND ON I-68 AS HE APPROACHED A LONG SWEEPING BEND IN THE ROAD HE ENTERED A THICK DENSE FOR BANK.  HE FAILED TO STAY ON THE ROAD AND THEN OVERTURNED.  THE FRONT RIGHT QUARTER SUSTAINED HEAVY DAMAGE AND SUBSEQUENT LEAKED WEAVERTOWN ENVIRONMENTAL GROUP WAS CONTACTED FOR CONTAINMENT AND MITIGATION.  LOCAL LEPC PROVIDED FIRST RESPONDER SERVICE. ALL CHEMICALS AND DEBRIS WERE REMOVED FROM THE SITE.

TRAILER LOADED, SITTING ON LOADING PAD.  PRODUCT STARTED DRIPPING FROM BELY SKIN.  PRODUCT PUMPED BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL STORAGE TANK.  CLEAN UP OF AREA PERFORMED BY FACILIITY PERSONNLE.  NOTE: COPY OF HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST NUMBER 00866749 COVERING THIS LOADING IS ATTACHED.  THIS MANIFEST WAS THEN UTILIZED FOR ACTUAL MOVEMENT WHEN PRODUCT LOADED ON A REPLACEMENT TRAILER.

WHILE INSPECTIN TRUCK, DRIVER NOTICED LIQUID DRIPPING IN SEVERAL PLACES FROM BOTTOM OF TRAILER.  THE DRIVER PLACED A TARP UNDER THE TRAILER TO CATCH AND CONTAIN THE LIQUID.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE CARGO, DRIVER SAW AN AREA ON THE TRAILER FLOOR APPROXIMATELY 5 FEET SQUARE THAT APPEARED TO BE WET AND TWO (2) DRUMS APPEARED TO BE LEAKING FROM AROUNF THE LIDS.  JONES BROTHERS COMPANY OF BOSSIER CITY, LA WAS CONTRACTED TO REMEDY THE LEAKING DRUMS AND PROVIDE ANY REMEDIATION THAT WAS NEEDED.  THIS WORK WAS DONE UNDER THE DIRECTION OF THE LOUISIANA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY. TWO DRUMS WERE FOUND TO HAVE DEFECTIVE GASKETS.  THESE LIDS WERE RESEALED. ONE ADDITIONAL DRUM OF CLEAN-UP DEBRIS WAS GENERATED WHICH WAS TAKEN ON TO THE DISPOSAL FACILITY WHERE IT WAS ACCEPTED UPON OFF LOADING AT MARINE SHALE PROCESSORS.  THE TRAILER WAS SENT BACK TO JONES BROTHER COMPANY FOR DECONTAMINATION.  THE FOLLOWING AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED.
DOCKMAN WAS LOADING FRIEGHT FROM DOCK TOOUTBOUND TRAILER.  HE TURNED SHORT TO GET THE FORKS UNDER A PALLET AND LET THE REAR OF THE TOWMOTOR BUMP AGAINST 1 BOX BRAKING 1 4 LITER OF PRODUCT.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM CLEAN HARBORS OF BRAINTREE, INC. LOCATED AT 385 QUINCY AVENUE IN BRAINTREE, MA TO APTUS, INC. LOCATED AT 21750 CEDAR AVENUE IN LAKEVILLE, MN.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE INTENDED RECEIVING FACILITY, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 1 PINT OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM A PINHOLE LEAK THAT HAD DEVELOPED ON THE SIDE OF ONE OF THE CONTAINERS ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE, ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY AND PLACED THE CONTAINERS INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM.  ALL CLEAN-UP DEBRIS GENERATED AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT WAS PLACED IN THE SALVAGE DRUMS AND DISPOSED OF AT THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE ORIGINAL SHIPPING DOCUMENT.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING WAS OBSERVED.  ALL LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND TO OVERPACK ANY CONTAINER THAT IS FOUND TO BE NOT STRUCTURALLY SOUND.

column168: A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM CHAMPION INTERNATIONAL CORP. LOCATED AT ONE RUNWAY RD IN SOUTH PORTLAND, ME TO CLEAN HARBORS OF CLEVELAND, INC. LOCATED AT 2900 BROADWAY IN CLEVELAND, OH.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE 2900 BROADWAY IN CLEVELAND, OH.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE INTENDED RECEIVING FACILITY, APPROXIMATELY 1-3 OUNCES OF MATERIAL ESCAPED FROM THE TOP LID OF ONE DRUM AS IT WAS BEING MOVED BY AN EMPLOYEE. THE EMPLOYEE MOVING THE DRUM EXPERIENCED A MINOR CHEMICAL BURN AS A RESULT OF THE RELEASE AND WAS TREATED A THTE SCENE IMMEDIATELY AND RETURNED TO WORK.  IT IS BELIVED THAT A DEFECTIVE CLOSURE DEVICE WAS THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE.  FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY TENDED TO THE EMPLOYEE WHO WAS INJURED, ABSORBED ALL REMAINING PRODUCT WITH SPEEDI DRY AND PLACED A NEW CLOSURE DEVICE ON THE DRUM.  THIS DRUM, ALONG WITH ALL CLEAN-UP DEBRIS WAS DISPOSED OF AT THE INTENDED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE ORIGINAL SHIPPING DOCUMENT.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED.  ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IF A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE STRUCTURALLY SOUND OR IF A CLOSURE DEVICE IS FOUND TO BE DEFECTIVE.

column168: THIS RELEASE OCCURRED FROM A DERAILED TANK CAR THAT WAS PUNCTURED ACCOUNT BEING STRUCK BY ANOTHER CAR IN THE TRAIN.  THE LOCATION OF THE DAMAGE WAS IN THE UPPER PORTION OF THE TANK CAR TANK.  THE CAUSE OF THE DERAILMENT WAS DETERMINED TO BE A RAPID BOLT HOLE BREAK IN A BONDED INSULATED RAIL JOINT.  THE MAJORITY OF THE REFRIGERANT GAS ESCAPED PRIOR TO AUTO-REFRIGERATION OCCURRING.  A PATCH WAS WELDED OVER THE HOLD TO RETAIN THE REMAINING PRODUCT IN THE TANK CAR AND TO PERMIT REPOSITIONING OF THE CAR TO CLEAR THE DERAILMENT.  ONCE CLEAR OF THE WRECKAGE, THE REMAINING PRODUCT WAS OFF LOADED INTO TANK TRUCKS.  AN ESTIMATED 400 RESIDENTS WERE EVACUATED ACCOUNT OF THE RELEASE.  THERE WERE 18 RESIDENTS TREATED AT THE SCENE BY EMTS, PLUS AN ADDITIONAL 10 TREATED AND RELEASED FROM AREA HOSPITAL.  BOTH TRAIN CREW MEMBERS WERE EXAMINED FOR INHALATION OF THE PRODUCT.  LOST TIME INJURY CASES ARE BEING FILED.

column168: AT 1315 HOURS DAMON WOODCOCK, ON SCENE COORDINATIOR FOR LARCO ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. ARRIVED AT THE SCENE OF AN INCIDENT INVOLVING A PPG TRACTOR TRAILER, SHIPPING 55 GALLONS 17-HE DRUMS OF METHYLAL AND TRICHLOROETHANE.  THE LOCATION OF THE INCIDENT WAS THE I-10 ENTRANCE RAMP WEST BOUND IN ROANOKE, LA.  AT 1330 HOURS RECOVERY TECHNICIANS RICKY MANUEL, MIKE BREAUX, SHAWN CORMIER AND SAFETY OFFICER CRAIG WINKLES ARRIVED AT THE SCENE.  AT 1335 HOURS DAMON WOODCOCK MET WITH PPG OFFICALS, CHIEF TOMMY DESHOTEL OF THE JENNINGS FIRE DEPARTMENT, AND TROOPER RICHARD ELLIOT OF THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE AND DECIDED THAT AN ENTRY WOULD BE MADE INBUNKER GEAR WITH S.C.B.A. AT 1345 HOURS DAMON WOODCOCK AND SHAWN CORMIER BEGAN TO DRESS OUT FOR ENTRY AND DECON IS SET UP.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1350 HOURS DAMON WOODCOCK AND SHAWN CORMIER OPENS TRAILER DOOR AND ENTERED TRAILER FOR RECON.  UPON ENTRY TO THE TRAILER LIQUID WERE FOUND ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER RIN SMALL AMOUNTS AND LIQUIDS WERE LEAKING FROM THE TIPS OF DRUMS.  AT 1410 HOURS DAMON WOODCOCK AND SHAWN CORMIER EXIT THE TRAILER.  DAMON WOODCOCK THEN DEBRIEFS WITH TROOPER ELLIOT OF LSPD AND CHEIF TOMMY DESHOTEL AND EXPLAINED THAT DRUMS WERE LEAKING FROM BUNGS AND LIQUIDS WERE ON THE FLOOR.  AT 1426 HOURS CHARLES KEENAN, DAMON WOODCOCK AND SHAWN CORMIER MADE A SECOND ENTRY FOR RECON. AT 1436 HOURS DAMON WOODCOCK, AND TEAM EXIT THE TRAILER AND DEBRIEF ONE MORE TIME.  DAMON EXPLAINED THAT THE DRUMS WERE ONLY LEAKING FROM THE BUNGS, NO LEAKS WERE APPARENT FROM DRUM DAMAGE.  DAMON STATED THAT ALL BUNGS HAD BEEN TIGHTENED AND THAT LARCO WOULD PUT FLOOR DRY ON FLOOR TO BIND FREE LIQUIDS.  TROOPER ELLIOT WAS INFORMED OF THESE PLANS AND AUTHORIZED THEM. AT 1505 HOURS DAMON WOODCOCK ENTERS TO TAKE PICTURES.  AT 1510 HOURS MIKE BREAUX AND RICKY MANUEL ENTER, PLACING OIL DRY ON THE FLOOR OF TRAILER. AT 1543 HOURS THE JOB WAS COMPLETE.

column168: ON 10/03/95, AT 03:20 SORT SUPERVISOR JOHN SPRIGGS REPORTED A LEAKING SHIPMENT TO HAZMAT BASE.  THE SHIPMENT WAS LOCATED IN "A" BUILDING OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177.  HAZMAT SPILL TECH ALAN HENDERSON RESPONDED TO THE SPILL.  UPON ARRIVAL, HE FOUND 4 BROWN FIBREBOARD BOXES LEAKING AN OILY SUBSTANCE.  HE PH'D THE LIQUID, PH WAS NEUTRAL, THE OUTSIDE OF THE BOXES WERE MARKED AS FOLLOWS:  PAINT, 3, UN1263, PGIII, LTD. QTY.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS OF THE BOXES, EACH BOX CONTAINED 24 METAL ONE PINT RECEPTACLES, EACH HAVING A MANUFACTURER LABEL INDICATING THE CONTENTS TO THE INNER RECEPTACLES HAVE SCREW CLOSURES WITH INNER FRICTION CLOSURES.  IT HAS NOT BEEN DETERMINED HOW MANY OF THE INNER METAL RECEPTACLES LEAKED. ALL HAVE A SMALL AMOUNT OF OIL ON THEM.  THERE WAS NO CERTIFICATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO THIS SHIPMENT.  THE SHIPMENT WAS BAGGED AND TAGGED TO BE HELD UNTIL CONFIRMATION OF THE CONTENTS CAN BE OBTAINED FROM THE SHIPPER IN THE FORM OF A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET.  A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET HAS BEEN OBTAINED,  FLASHPOINT INDICATED 105 O F, CERTIFICATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS SAFETY DATA SHEET WILL BE ATTACHED TO THIS REPORT.  TOTAL OF LEAKAGE WAS LESS THAN ONE OUNCE.

column168: ON 10/07/95 AT 00:26 PART TIME SORTER MARY HITCHMEN REPORTED A LEAKING BOX EMITTING AN ODOR OF INSECTICIDE TO HAZ MAT BASE.  HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SPILL TECHNICIANS DAVID JARRELL AND ALAN HENDERSON RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY DONNED AIR PURIFING RESPIRATORS, PH'D THE LIQUID, NEUTRAL READING, OPENED THE BROWN FIBREBOARD BOX AND FOUND, 5-14 OUNCE AEROSOL CANS OF "BEE BOPPER"  INSECT SPRAY.  ONE OF THE FIVE AEROSOL CANS LEAKED IT'S ENTIRE CONTENTS DUE TO THE SNAP CLOSURE BEING UNSECURE AND THE INNER SPRAY NOZZLE WAS OFF CAUSING THE LEAKAGE.  DUE TO AEROSOL CANS BEING REGULATED FOR AIR TRANSPORT.  THE BOX WAS RESEALED, PLACED INSIDE A PLASTIC BAG AND TAGGED FOR HOLD FOR FAA INVESTIGATION.  THIS SHIPMENT IS CURRENTLY UNDER LOCK AND KEY IN THE HAZMAT SECURITY CAGE PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.  THERE  WAS NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THIS SHIPMENT WAS A REGULATED MATERIAL. THIS SHIPMENT WILL REMAIN ON HOLD IN THE HAZMAT SECURITY UNTIL INVESTIGATION AND RELEASED BY THE FAA.

ON 10-04-95 LEAD RAM LOADER RON BASHORE REPORTED A SHIPMENT, INTHE BELLY OF THE AIRCRAFT THAT SHOWED SIGNS OF WETNESS.  I, MICHAEL A. FRYE, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATIOR AND DAVID JARRELL, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TECHNICIAN RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL ON THE SCENE THERE WAS FIBERBOARD BOX THAT SHOWED SIGNS OF WETNESS ON THE BOTTOM.  UPON INVESTIGATION OF THE INNER CONTENTS WE FOUND 6, 15 OUNCE CAPACITY PLASTIC RECEPTACLES THAT WERE LYING ON THEIR SIDE.  THESE WERE LOADED AGAINST PROPER ORIENTATION.  THERE WAS NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THE CLOSURES.  THE INFO. ON THE LABEL STATED "CAL-STAT, 60% ISOPROPYL ALCOHOL".  THERE WERE 22 PIECES IN THIS SHIPMENT.  THREE OTHER BOXES CONTAINED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  ONE CONTAINED AN AEROSOL RECEPTACLE.  ONE CONTAINS A 4 OUNCE PLASTIC RECEPTACLE OF "CAL-STAT".  THE LAST ONE CONTAINED 2, ROAD SAFETY KITS.  EACH KIT CONTAINING 1 AEROSOL RECEPTACLE, 8 OUNCE CAPACITY AND 2 SAFETY FLARES. ALL OTHER PIECES IN THIS SHIPMENT WERE FOUND NOT TO CONTAIN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  NONE OF THESE PIECES WERE PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED OR PROPER CETIFICATION ACCOMPANIED TO INDICATE THESE WERE REGULATED AS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  ALL 22 PIENCES ARE AT THE HAZMAT SORT, IN THE SECURITY CAGE, UNDER LOCK AND KEY, PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.  THE PIECES THAT DID NOT CONTAIN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WERE FORWARDED ONTO SIGNATURE OF PERSON FILING REPORT.

ON 10-05-95 HAZ MAT AREA MANAGER, JIM CURTIS REPORTED A SHIPMENT IN THE HAZ MAT SORT, EMITTING AN ODOR.  HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TECHNICIAN, DIANE FIGUEROA AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TECHNICIAN, SUE HICKEY RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL ON THE SCENE THE AREA IN QUESTION WAS SECURED.  TECHNICIAN FIGUEORA DONNED A "LEVEL B" CHEMICAL SUIT AND A SELF CONTAINED BREATHING APPARATUS TO ENTER THE AREA.  ONCE IN THE AREA SHE FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX THAT WAS SET ON THE BOTTOM WITH SOME LIQUID ON THE FLOOR.  UPON INVESTIGATION OF THE INNER CONTENTS SHE FOUND A PLASTIC BAG.  INSIDE THIS PLASTIC BAG WAS A GLASS RECEPTACLE.  THIS GLASS RECEPTACLE WAS SHATTERED. THERE WAS A FIBERBOARD PROTECTIVE COVER AROUND THIS RECEPTACLE AND AROUND ALL THIS WAS SOME ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THE GLASS RECEPTACLE FAILED ALLOWING THE ENTIRE CONTENTS TO LEAK.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANIED.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND BE FORWARDED BACK TO THE SHIPPER VIA HIGHWAY.

ON MONDAY THE 2ND OF OCTOBER AT 1100 HRS. MGR. H.W. RODABOUGH WAS NOTIFIED BY MR. JOHN LYON M.T.O. AT OGDEN UT. THAT TANKCAR GATX 7230 IS LEAKING. IT IS LOCATED FIRST OUT ON THE WEST END OF TRACK #13 WAITING FOR REPAIR. INSPECTION REVEALED RUPTURE DISC BROKEN, WITH PRODUCT RUNNING DOWN BOTH SIDES OF THE CAR. MGR. RODABOUGH REPLACED THE DISC WITH BS&B 100# DISC, SAFETY VENT LOCATED ON THE MANWAY COVER AND WAS THE BAFFLED VARIETY. CAR WAS WASHED WITH SODA WATER SOLUTION AND RELEASED, CHEMTREC NOTIFIED MRS. TRACY JACKSON WAS FURNISHED WITH DETAILS AND ASSIGNED CASE #39273. MRS. JAN PEOBLE OR MAGMA COOPER WAS ALSO NOTIFIED.

WHILE CONDUCTING REGULATORY COMPLIANCE INSPECTIONS AT OGDEN UT. MGR. C.T.S. H.W. RODABOUGH INSPECTED TANKCAR GATX44994 LOAD SODIUM HYDROXIDE. NOTED FRANGIBLE INSPECTED HAD FAILED. MGR. RODABOUGH INSTALLED BS&B 100# DISC IN BAFFLED SAFETY VENT MOUNTED ON MANWAY COVER. CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED MRS. TRACY JACKSON, FURNISHED WITH DETAILS AND CASE NUMBER 39274 WAS ASSIGNED. ELF ATOCHEM WAS ALSO NOTIFIED, MR. KEN ROLLA PRODUCTION MGR. AT THE PORTLAND PLANT.

MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, DURING COMPLIANCE INSPECTION OF BNRR TRANSFER, TRAIN YARD 19, DENVER YARDS, NOTED TANK CAR DAX 7106, LEAKING FROM 2-INCH UNLOADING CONNECTION VALVE NOZZLE. INSPECTION REVEALED THAT NOZZLE THREADS WERE FREE FROM TAPE AND THREADS APPEARED TO BE STRESSED. SEALED THREADS AND SECURED VALVE, WHICH STOPPED LEAK. column168: TANK CAR GATX 97838, AMMONIA, ANHYDROUS, LIQUEFIED, WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING BY A SWITCH CREW.  RAILROAD RESPONDERS WERE NOTIFIED.  INSPECTION OF THE CAR REVEALED THAT THE CAR HAD DEVELOPED A LEAK FROM THE MANWAY COVER PLATE GASKET.  UNICAL, PORTLAND, OR, WAS CONTACTED TO DETERMINE IF THEY WOULD ACCEPT THE CAR.  UNICAL AGREED TO ACCEPT THE CAR.  THE LEAKING CAR MOVED BNSF VANCOUVER, WA TO UNICAL, PORTLAND, OR VIA THE UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD UNDER EMERGENCY EXEMPTION DOT-E-99999 WHERE IT WAS UNLOADED.  THE CAR WILL BE RELEASED FROM UNICAL FOR MOVEMENT TO THE TRANSCISCO TANK CAR SHOP AT MILE CITY, MONTANA.

ON 10/08/95, A SPILL WITH AN ODOR WAS REPORTED AT THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SORT AREA.  HAZARDOUS MATERIAL COORDINATOR, ADDIE CAMPTON AND SPILL TECHNICIAN, JEFF MCLAUGHLN RESPONDED.  UPON THEIR ARRIVAL THEY COULD SEE A ALDRICH BOX WHICH APPEARED TO HAVE THE BOTTOM SATURATED WITH A FLAMMABLE LIQUID.  AFTER DONNING THEIR PROTECTIVE GEAR, THEY BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION OF THE SHIPMENT.  WE FOUND THE INNER CONTENTS TO CONTAIN A MATERIAL CALLED "METHYL METHACRYLATE MONOMER, INHIBITED, 3, FLAMMABLE LIQUID, UN1247 PG. 11.  THIS WAS IN A BROWN GLASS RECEPTACLE, CONTAINING APPROX:  2 LITRES.  THIS WAS PACKED WITH CARDBOARD AROUND THE LID AND THE ABSORBENT USED WAS VERMICULITE, ALL PACKED IN A PLASTIC BAG.  WHEN INSPECTING THE GLASS RECEPTACLE WE FOUND THE BOTTOM OF THE RECEPTACLE TO HAVE BEEN BROKEN.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS THEN PROPERLY REPACKED IN A RECOVERY DRUM AND ALL MARKINGS AND LABELS WERE APPLIED.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED AND THE PROPER CERTIFICATION DID ACCOMPANY THIS SHIPMENT.  THE ONLY THEORY WE HAVE FOR THIS SHIPMENT LEAKING WAS FAILURE OF THE BASIC PACKING MATERIAL.  CLEAR OF SCENE 11:00

IN THE HAZMAT SORT, LEAKING AND EMITTING AN ODOR.  HAZARDOUS MATERIAL COORDINATOR ADDIE CAMPTON AND SPILL TECHNICIAN, TAMMY FLORENCE RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND THE AREA HAD BEEN SECURED.  AFTER DONNING OF THEIR PROTECTIVE GEAR THEY CONTINUED THEIR INSPECTION OF THE SCENE.  THEY DISCOVERED A WET FIBERBOARD BOX.  THIS SHIPMENT HAD LEAKED ON ABOUT SIX OTHER PIECES OF FREIGHT.  UPON OPENING OF THIS SHIPMENT THEY DISCOVERED A BROWN GLASS BOTTLE APPROX:  ONE GALLON IN SIZE INNER CONTENTS THEY FOUND THAT THE BOTTOM OF THE GLASS CONTAINER HAD BROKEN. THIS WAS AN ALDRICH SHIPMENT AND THE PACKAGE WAS PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED A REGULATED MATERIAL AND THE PROPER CERTIFICATION DID ACCOMPANY THIS SHIPMENT.  PACKAGE WAS MARKED AS FOLLOWS: "TETACHLOROETHYLENE, 6.1, POIONOUS, MATERIALS, UN1897, PG 111, LTD. QTY. THE ONLY THEORY WE HAVE FOR THIS SHIPMENT LEAKING WAS THE BASIC PACKING MATERIAL.  THIS WILL BE REPACKED IN A SALVAGE DRUM AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  CLEAR OF SCENE 03:04.

column168: 03:58 THURSDAY OCTOBER 12, 1995, HAZMAT LEAD RHONDA CLONCH REPORTED A LEAKING SHIPMENT TO HAZMAT BASE.  THE LEAKING SHIPMENT WAS LOCATED IN THE HAZMAT SORT AREA OF OUR FACILITY LOCATED AT 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHION 45177.  HAZMAT COORDINATOR TONY FRYE AND HAZMAT SPILL TECHNICIAN CAROLYN CORDREY RESPONDED TO THE SPILL.  UPON ARRIVAL, THEY FOUND A BROWN FIBREBOARD BOX, THE BOTTOM OF THE BOX SHOWED SIGNS OF LEAKAGE, PH WAS NOT ABLE TO BE OBTAINED DUE TO THE LEAKAGE AREA WAS TOO DRY TO OBTAIN A READING.  THE OUTSIDE OF THE BOX WAS MARKED "CORROSIVE LIQUID N.O.S., UN1760 AND LABELED WITH A CLASS 8 HAZARD LABEL.  ORIENTATION ARROWS WERE REPRINTED ON THE BOX.  THEY OPENED THE BOX AND FOUND 2 500 ML PLASTIC BOTTLES WITH SCREW TYPE CLOSURES, THERE WAS NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THE CLOSURES.  EACH BOTTLE CONTAINED APPROX: 250ML OF LIQUID.  THERE WAS VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE AROUND EACH OF THE BOTTLE CLOSURES.  TOTAL AMOUNT OF LIQUID LOST WAS APPROX: ONE OUNCE.  EACH BOTTLE WAS LABELED IN THE FOLLOWING MANOR:  "AFB-DIGESTANT BASE".  THESE BOTTLES WERE PACKED INSIDE THE BROWN FIBREBOARD BOX WITH STYROFOAM PEANUTS AROUND EACH BOTTLE, AND FIBREBOARD DIVIDERS.  THE BOX WAS RESEALED AND PLACED INSIDE 2 PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBANT MATERIAL AND PLACED UNDER LOCK AND KEY IN THE CORROSIVE CABINET LOCATED IN OUR HAZMAT SORT AREA.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PACKED IN A BOX INTENDED FOR SOLID USE ONLY, WITH NO HAZMAT CERTIFICATION ATTACHED.  THIS SHIPMENT WILL REMAIN ON HOLD UNTIL PROPER CERTIFICATION AND PACKAGING ARE RECEIVED.

ON 10/12/95 LEAD RAMP LOADER, BRIAN HIENZ REPORTED A SHIPMENT, ON THE AIRCRAFT PARKING APRON EMITTING AN ODOR.  I, MICHAEL A. FRYE, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TECHNICIAN, KEN HAAG RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL ON THE SCENE THE FIBERBOARD BOX WAS ISOLATED. TECHNICIAN HAAG DONNED AN ORGAINIC VAPOR CARTRIDGE RESPIRATOR TO INVESTIGATE THE INNER CONTENTS.  INSIDE HE FOUND FOUR INNER FIBERBOARD BOXES.  EACH CONTAINED SIX INNER FIBERBOARD BOXES.  INSIDE THESE BOXES WERE SIX GLASS RECEPTACLES.  ONE OF THESE GLASS RECEPTACLES WAS BROKEN. THESE INNER FIBERBOARD BOXES HAVE SEPERATION PIECES TO KEEP THE GLASS RECEPTACLES APART.  ONE OF THESE PIECES BROKE DOWN ALLOWING THE GLASS RECEPTACLES TO COME IN CONTACT WITH EACH OTHER, CAUSING ONE TO BREAK. THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANINED.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND FORWARDED ONTO ITS DESTINATION.

ON 10-11-95 HAZMAT SORT SUPERVISOR, TERRY CAIN REPORTED A UNIT LOAD DEVICE EMITTING AN ODOR.  I, MICHAEL A. FRYE, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TECHNICIAN, KEN HAAG RESPONDED.  TECHNICIAN HAAG DONNED AN ORGANIC VAPOR CARTRIDGE RESPIRATOR TO INVESTIGATE THE INNER CONTENTS OF THE UNIT LOAD DEVICE.  INSIDE HE FOUND A METAL RECEPTACLE WHICH WAS NOT PROPERLY BLOCKED AND BRACED IN THE UNIT LOAD DEVICE.  THIS METAL RECEPTACLE HAD A FIVE GALLON CAPACITY.  THERE WAS A DENT ON THE SIDE TOWARDS THE TOP.  THIS RECEPTACLE HAD A SCREW TYPE CLOSURE WITH POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE.  SOME OF THE CONTENTS WAS ON TOP OF THIS RECEPTACLE.  DUE TO THE DENT IN THE SIDE, WE BELIEVE THAT THIS CAUSED THE CLOSURE TO FAIL. THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPAINED.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND FORWARDED ONTO DESTINATION.

DSR NELSON MORALES WAS UNLOADIG TRAILER WHEN HE RAN UP ON A PAIL SITTING ON TRAILER FLOOR.  THE TIRE FORCED THE PAIL INTO A SKID CAUSING A PUNCTURE HOLE IN THE PAIL.  NELSON WAS TALKED TO ABOUT THE INCIDENT AND WILL BE MORE CAUTIOUS IN THE FUTURE.

DRIVER ALL YAKULEVICH WAS STRIPPING THE TRAILER.  HAD FORKS TOO HIGH IN ATTEMPTING TO LIFT SKID THAT HAD 1 - 55 GALLON DRUM (CORROSIVE) AND 11 - 5 GAL PAILS (NON-REGULATED).  THE FORK PUNCTURED 1 - 5 GALLON PAIL AND THE 1 - 55 GALLON DRUM. HE DID NOT NOTICE LEAKAGE UNTIL SKID WAS OUT OF 48' TRAILER AND ON DOCK.  AT THAT TIME MIKE SUYDEN (FOS) NOTICED PROBLEM AND TOOK PROPER STEPS TO STOP SPILLAGE AND CLEAN UP SPILLED MATERIAL. SITUATION COULD HAVE BEEN AVOIDED BY AL PAYING CLOSER ATTENTION TO WHAT HE WAS DOING.  ALSO, IF PLASTIC DRUMS WERE NOT ON SKID, BUT LOOSE, OCCURANCE WOULD HAVE BEEN AVOIDED ALSO.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 2230 HRS 10/11/95, UNION PACIFIC EMPLOYEES OBSERVED PRODUCT COMING FROM THE TOP OF THE TANK CAR WHILE THE CAR WAS BEING MOVED. CAR WAS CONSEQUENTLY ISOLATED UNTIL INSPECTION AND REPAIRS COULD BE COMPLETED.  ON 10/12/95 CAR WAS INSPECTED BY UPRR SPECIAL AGENT-HAZARDOUS MATERIALS K.C. DECHANT.  INSPECTION DISCLOSED NO EVIDENCE OF PRODUCT RESIDUE ON SIDES OF CAR, WITH THE AMOUNT OF RESIDUE VISIBLE NEAR VALVES AND FITTINGS ON THE TOP OF THE CAR INSUFFICIENT TO DETERMINE THE SOURCE. THE TANK CAR WAS MANUFACTURED 8/95, WITH NO UMLER RECORD OF PRIOR MOVEMENT UNDER LOAD.  OPENING  OF THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE RESULTED IN THE RELEASE OF VAPOR FROM THE TANK.  INSPECTION OF VALVES AND FITTINGS DISCLOSED THE FOLLOWING:  -ONE MANWAY COVER BOLT WAS LESS THAN HAND TIGHT, THE REMAINDER LESS THAN WRENCH TIGHT.  -ALL BOLTS LOOSE ON VALVE HOUSING NOZZLE FLANGE. -ALL (4) LIQUID EDUCTION VALVE BODY FLANGE BOLTS LOOSE.  -ALL (4) LIQUID EDUCATION VALVE BODY FLANGE BOLTS LOOSE.  -ALL (4) LIQUID EDUCTION VALVE UNLOADING CONNECTION FLANGE BOLTS LOOSE.  -ALL (4) AIR INLET VALVE BODY FLANGE BOLTS SUFFICIENTLY LOOSE TO ALLOW MOVEMENT OF THE ENTIRE ASSEMBLY. -ALL (4) MAGNETIC GAUGING DEVICE FLANGE BOLTS LOOSE.  -3 OF 4 RELIEF VALVE FLANGE BOLTS LOOSE.  DECHANT TIGHTENED ALL BOLTS.  IT WAS NOTED THAT THE CAR HAD BEEN PAINTED FOLLOWING THE LAST TORQUEING OF ALL BOLTS EXCEPT THOSE ON THE MANWAY COVER, AS A LAYER OF PAINT HAD DRIED OVER THE THREADS AND HAD TO BE BROKEN TO SECURE THE FITTINGS.  INSPECTION REQUIRED REMOVAL OF SEALS UPK-830104 (VALVE HOUSING) AND UPK-830102/103 (MANWAY).  THE VALVE HOUSING AND MANWAY WERE RE-SEALED WITH UPE-277470, RESPECTIVELY. CHEMTREC FILE NUMBER 38478.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 2230 HRS 10/11/95, UNION PACIFIC EMPLOYEES OBSERVED PRODUCT COMING FROM THE TOP OF THE TANK CAR WHILE THE CAR WAS BEING MOVED. CAR WAS CONSEQUENTLY ISOLATED UNTIL INSPECTION AND REPAIRS COULD BE COMPLETED.  ON 10/12/95 CAR WAS INSPECTED BY UPRR SPECIAL AGENT-HAZARDOUS MATERIALS K.C. DECHANT.  THERE WAS EVIDENCE OF PRODUCT RESIDUE ON THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE CAR, DIRECTLY BENEATH THE MANWAY; HOWEVER, WAS VERY SLIGHT AND CONFINED TO THE TOP 1/4 OF THE CAR.  OPENING OF THE VACCUM RELIEF VALVE RESULTED IN THE RELEASE OF VAPOR FORM THE TANK, UNDER SLIGHT PRESSURE.  THE TANK CAR WAS MANUFACTURED 09/95, WITH NO RECORD OF A PRIOR MOVEMENT UNDER LOAD.  INSPECTION DISCLOSED THE FOLLOWING.  2 ADJACENT MANWAY COVER BOLTS WERE LOOSE (OF 8).  THESE WERE IMMEDIATELY ADJACENT TO THE AREA OF SPILLAGE.  THE GASKET WAS PROPERLY POSITIONED AND IN GOOD CONDITION.  5 BOLTS WERE LOOSE ON THE VALVE HOUSING NOZZLE FLANGE.  ALL OTHER FITTINGS WERE FOUND PROPERLY SECURED.  ABOVE EXCEPTIONS WERE CORRECTED FOLLOWING INSPECTION.  WITH RESPECT TO THE LOOSE BOLTS ON THE VALVE HOUSING FLANGE, ALL HAD BEEN PAINTED OVER SINCE LAST HAVING BEEN TORQUED, INDICATING THE CAR HAD PROPERLY COME FROM THE MANUFACTURER THE PREVIOUS MONTH WITH THE FITTING LOOSE.  INSPECTION REQUIRED REMOVAL OF SEAL UPK-730106 FROM THE VALVE HOUSING.  THIS WAS RESEALED FOLLOWING INSPECTION WITH UPE-277472.  SEAL UPK-830105 WAS NOTED INTACT ON THE MANWAY COVER, DID NOT REQUIRE REMOVAL FOR GASKET INSPECTION.  IT WAS ALSO NOTED THAT A CONSIDERABLE AMOUNT OF LIQUID HAD SPLASHED ONTO THE RIGHT SIDE OF THIS TANK CAR, A-END, FROM THE AREA OF THE R-3 WHEEL, AND COULD HAVE BEEN MISTAKEN, FROM A DISTANCE, FOR PRODUCT LEAKAGE.  THIS LIQUID WAS PRESENT DUE TO EXTERNAL FACTORS, AND NOT LEAKAGE FROM THE TANK CAR.  CHEM- TREC FILE NUMBER 39478.
FORKLIFT PUNCTURED 2 55 GALLON DRUMS WHILE UNLOADING PALLET IN FRONT OF DRUMS.  SPILL CONTAINED FOR DISPOSITION.

WHILE CUTTING CARS WITH A TRACK AT CSX YARD IN FLORENCE, SC A TANK CAR SLOSHED PRODUCT FROM THE TOP AND SPLASHED AND EMPLOYEE.  MR LARRY EDWARDS WAS SPLASHED WITH DROPS OF ACID ON HIS ARMS AND BACK.  MR. EDWARDS WENT TO SHOWER IMMEDIATELY AND WASHED ANY ACID OFF.  THERE WAS NO INJURY AND MR. EDWARDS DID NOT SEEK MEDICAL ATTENTION.  CSXT RESPONDED CONTRACTOR TO REPAIR CAR.  CONTRACTOR REPLACED A BLOWN RUPTURE DISK AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED.

column42: FORMIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 85% ACID BY MASS
column168: CONSULTED DECISION TREE. PUT ON APPROPRIATE PPE AND REFERRED TO CORROSIVE RESPONSE SHEET. SPILL WAS CONTAINED WITHIN INNER PLASTIC LINER OF CARTON. CARTON STAINED BECAME DAMP FROM FLUID, SOME FLUID LEAKING FROM LINER. ENTIRE SPILL ABSORBED BY CARTON. MOVED PACKAGE FROM PACKAGE CAR INTO OPEN AIR. USED PH TAPE, DETERMINED TO BE ACID, APPLIED SODIUM BICARBONATE TO NEUTRALIZE TO PH OF 7. MIXED CLAY BASE ABSORBANT. ALL WASTE AND CARTON RETURN TO BUILDING. WASTE DISPOSED OF THROUGH DMP. REMAINING 3 LITERS REPACKED AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Water Damage
column168: ON 10/06/95 LOWELL CENTER HAD AN ON ROAD SPILL.  RICH MURRAY BEING A FIRST RESPONDER, WENT TO GET DAMAGED PACKAGE.  HE USED DECISION TREE, CORROSIVE RESPONSE SHEETS, AND PROPER PPE AT SITE.  HE CLEANED SMALL SPILL ON PACKAGE CAR FLOOR, AND RETURNED TO THE HUB WITH CONTAMINATED MATERIALS FOR PROCESSING.  ONE CAP OF FOUR PLASTIC CONTAINERS WAS OFF.  I THEN CONSULTED MY DECISION TREE, CORROSIVE RESPONSE SHEETS, AND USED PPE TO PROCESS THE WET MATERIALS THROUGH THE DMP.

ON 10-24-95 A SPILL WAS REPORTED AT THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SORT FACILITY WITH AN ODOR BY LEAD, MARY LATHREM.  HAZARDOUS MATERIAL COORDINATOR, ADDIE CAMPTON AND SPILL TECHNICIAN JEFF MCLAUGHLIN RESPONDED.  UPON THEIR INVESTIGATION THEY FOUND A WET FIBREBOARD BOX EMITTING AN ODOR.  WE THEN BEGAN OUR INSPECTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS.  WE DISCOVERED A 7 PIECE PERFUME SHIPMENT, ONE OF WHICH WAS LEAKING.  EACH OF THE BOXES CONTAINED APPROX. 24 8 OZ. BOTTLES OF PERFUME.  OF WHICH ONE WAS LEAKING.  THE SHIPMENTS WERE CLEARLY MARKED AND LABELED AS A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL AND THE PROPER CERTIFICATION DID ACCOMPANY THIS SHIPMENT.  THE ONLY THEORY WE HAVE FOR THIS SHIPMENT LEAKING IS POSSIBLE RUBBING AND FRICTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS CAUSING THE CLOSURE TO BECOME LOOSE AND LEAKING.  6 OF 7 OF THE BOXES WERE FORWARDED ON AND THE LEAKING SHIPMENT WAS REPACKED IN A RECOVERY DRUM WITH ALL LABELS AND MARKINGS APPLIED AND THE PROPER CERTIFICATION ATTACHED AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  CLEAR OF SCENE 02:10.

FORKLIFT DRIVER WAS MOVING A DOCK CART TO THE LOADING DOOR, WHILE IN ROUTE TO THE (1) CTN FELL OFF AND WAS RUN OVER BY THE FORKLIFT.  ABOUT 6 LBS OF SPILLAGE WAS CLEANED UP BY ROGER LEWIS/ATM & JOEY GIACCAGLINI/FOM. FORKLIFT DRIVER KITTY PUGH COMPLAINED ABOUT CHEST PAINS, SHE DID GO TO THE MEDICAL CTR FOR A CHECK UP, SHE IS STILL OFF FROM WORK.  THE POISONOUS MATERIAL ALONG WITH THE WASTE WAS PLACED IN 3 FIVE GALLON PAILS AND IS AWAITING DISPOSAL BY FERGUSON HARBOR.

HE REPORTED THE RESIDUE TO SUPERVISOR MITCHELL WHITESIDE WHO OPENED THE TRAILER DOOR TO INVESTIGATE AND FOUND ONE EMPTY 5 GALLON CONTAINER SETTING ON ONE OF THE SKIDS, THE CONTENTS APPEARED TO HAVE LEAKED ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR.  THE RESIDUE APPEARED TO BE DRY.  THERE SHOULD HAVE BEEN A SHEET OF CARDBOARD BETWEEN THE PALLET AND CONTAINERS WHICH WOULD HAVE PREVENTED A NAIL FROM THE SKID COMING IN CONTACT WITH THE BOTTOM OF THE CONTAINER.

JOE DEBNAM WAS FURNISHED WITH DETAILS AND ASSIGNED CASE 39566.  ALSO NOTIFIED WAS MR. TOM BEYERSDORF, ACID PLANT ENGINEER FOR KENNECOTT UTAH COPPER.

WHILE CONDUCTING REGULATORY COMPLIANCE INSPECTIONS AT OGDEN UT. MGR. H.W. RODABOUGH INSPECTED TANKCAR ADMX 30356, RESIDUE CAR LAST CONTAINED DENATURED ALCOHOL, NOTED THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER IN THE OPEN POSITION, FURTHER INVESTIGATION REVEALED THE 1" AIR CONNECTION VALVE PLUG, HANGING ON THE CHAIN AND THE VALVE IN THE OPEN POSITION. GENE SMITH, DIRECTOR OF CORPORATE LOSS PREVENTION FOR ADM CORN SWEETNERS WAS ALSO INFORMED REGARDING DETAILS.

AT APPROXIMATELY 1645  HRS 10/17/95, AN FRA INSPECTOR OBSERVED POSSIBLE LEAKAGE FROM TANK CAR TILX 100243 IN THE UNION PACIFIC  SOUTH OMAHA YARD. THIS INFORMATION WAS PROVIDED TO UPRR THE FOLLOWING MORNING.  RAILCAR WAS INSPECTED BY UPRR SPECIAL AGENT- HAZARDOUS MATERIALS K.C. DENCHANT, WHO NOTED EVIDENCE OR PRODUCT HAVING RUN DOWN BOTH SIDES OF THE TANK, DIRECTLY BENEATH THE SAFETY VENT HOUSING.  SUBSEQUENT INSPECTION DISCLOSED THE CAR WAS EQUIPPED WITH A 100# FDI DISC, WHICH HAD RUPTURED.  THERE WAS CONSIDERABLE DETERIORATION OF THE PAINT AT THE TOP AND ON THE SIDES OF THE TANK WHERE MATERIAL HAD SPILLED; HOWEVER, NO RESIDUAL LIQUID WAS NOTED ON THE CAR OR ON THE GROUND.  DECHANT REPLACED THE FRANGIBLE DISC WITH AN IDENTICAL 100# FDI DISC.  ALL OTHER FITTINGS WERE FOUND TO BE SECURE, AND CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT AT 1320 HRS 10/18/95.  CHEMTREC WAS FURNISHED DETAILS OF THE INCIDENT, WITH SUBSEQUENT SHIPPER NOTIFICATION FOR REPORTING PURPOSES.  CHEMTREC FILE 36916.

ON TUESDAY THE 17TH DAY OF OCTOBER AT 1300 HRS. MGR. H.W. RODABOUGH WAS NOTIFIED BY MR. CRAIG JENSEN, M.Y.O. AT OGDEN UT.  THAT TANKCAR ADMX 29392 WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM AND WOULD BE SET OUT ON TRACK, SHORT 24 FOR REPAIR.  INSPECTION REVEALED THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM AROUND THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP.  THE VALVE OPERATING HANDLE WAS IN THE CLOSED POSITION.  MGR. RODABOUGH REMOVED THE OUTLET NOZZLE CAP, DRAINED THE CONTENTS AND CHECKED THE GASKET, WHICH WAS FOUND TO BE IN BAD ORDER. MGR. RODABOUGH APPLIED A TEMPORARY GORTEX GASKET AND REPLACED THE CAP, THIS ACTION CONTAINED THE LEAK.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED AND CHEMTREC NOTIFIED MR. JIM COOPER FURNISHED WITH DETAILS AND ASSIGNED CASE 39610.  THE VALVE A JAMESBURY WAFER-SPHERE VALVE IS IN NEED OF REPAIR AND SHOULD EITHER BE REPLACED OR REPAIRED BEFORE BEING RELOADED.  MR. ANDY ALLEN, PLANT TRAFFIC COORDINATIOR FOR THE SHIPPER, ARCHER DANIELS MIDLAND WAS ALSO NOTIFIED.

ON 101895 AT APPROXIMATELY 8AM, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, GEOFFREY REEDER WAS MAKING ROUTINE TANK CAR INSPECTIONS AT SETTEGAST YARD IN HOUSTON, TEXAS.  WHILE INSPECTING THIS CAR, REEDER NOTICED THE ODOR OF VINYL ACETATE.  OPENING THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER, A HISS WAS HEARD COMING FROM THE LIQUID EDUCTION VALVE.  REEDER CHECKED THE VALVE TO MAKE CERTAIN IT WAS CLOSED.  WHEN THE VALVE HANDLE WAS MOVED, A BURST OF VAPOR CAME FROM AROUND THE VALVE STEM PACKING.  REEDER TIGHTENED THE PACKING NUT ABOUT 3/4 OF A TURN.  THIS SECURED THE VALVE.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO MOVE WITHOUT DELAY.  CHEMTREC, THE SHIPPER, AND CONSIGNEE WERE NOTIFIED.

column168: ON OCTOBER 23, 1995 AT 7:30 A.M. MR. ROGER SCHMIDT CALLED AND ASKED FOR QUOTES ON TWO LOADS OF FUEL. ABOUT TEN MINUTES AFTER WE TALKED HE CALLED BACK AND ORDERED THE LOADS WHICH ARE 7000 GALLONS EACH. HE INSTRUCTED US TO HAUL THE ONE TO HIS BUS GARAGE FIRST AS HE DID NOT WANT TO RUN OUT. OUR DRIVER WAS COMING THRU THEIR THAT MORNING SO I INSTRUCTED HIM TO DROP OFF A 1000 GALLONS IN ORDER SO THEY WOULD NOT RUN OUT. THE NEXT DAY AT 3:00 P.M. OCTOBER 24, 1995 WE CAME WITH THE BALANCE OF THEIR LOAD WHICH WAS 6000 GALLONS. OUR DRIVER UNLOADED HIS FIRST COMPARTMENT WHICH IS 2500. THEN HE PROCEEDED TO UNLOAD HIS SECOND COMPARTMENT. AFTER ABOUT 3 1/2 MINUTES THE FUEL CAME PUSHING OUT THE VENT PIPE SO HE IMMEDIATELY SHUT EVERYTHING DOWN. OUR DRIVER CALLED ME RIGHT AWAY AND TOLD ME WHAT HAD HAPPENED. I THEN CALLED AGASSIZ ENVIRONMENTAL AND TALKED TO JOHN LANDWEHR TO FIND OUT HOW QUICK THEY COULD GET THERE AND IF THEY HAD SOME EQUIPMENT WE COULD USE TO START THE CLEANUP. HE TOLD ME HE WOULD CONTACT THE PROPER PEOPLE AT THE PCA ABOUT THE RELEASE AND HE DID. I THEN WENT UP THE SIGHT MYSELF AND ACCESS THE SPILL. WHILE IN ROUTE I CALLED OUR DRIVER AND TOLD HIM THAT HE SHOULD DIKE ANY CALVERTS THAT IT COULD POSSIBLE FLOW THRU. HE THEN TOLD ME HE HAD TALKED TO THE OWNER WHICH WAS THE PERSON WHO ORDERED THE LOAD AND THAT THE OWNER SAID THAT HE MUST HAVE CALCULATED WRONG WHEN HE ORDERED THE LOAD. WHEN I ARRIVED AT THE SIGHT I SEEN THAT THE DRIVER HAD DIKED THE ONE CALVERT THAT IT COULD HAVE FLOWED THRU. AFTER INSPECTING THE SIGHT WE LAYED OUT CONTAINMENT BOOMS IN THE DITCH TO MAKE SURE THAT THE PRODUCT WOULD NOT SPREAD, WE ALSO USED ABSORB PADS TO PICK UP SOME FREE PRODUCT THAT WAS ON THE GROUND. I THEN CALLED THE LOCAL AUTHORITIES, I TALKED TO JOHN TO MAKE SURE HE CALLED THE PCA, HE DID, I THEN CALLED THE NRC. WE CONTRACTED AGASSIZ ENVIRONMENTAL TO DO THE REST OF THE CLEAN UP AND FOR THE TRANSPORTATION AND THE DISPOSAL THE CONTAMINATED PRODUCTS. I THEN TALKED TO MR. SCHMITZ AND TOLD THEM THAT THEY SHOULD STICK THE TANK BEFORE ORDERING A LOAD OF FUEL, HE THEN TOLD ME THE SAME THING HE TOLD OUR DRIVER THAT HE MADE A MISTAKE IN CALCULATING ALSO HE SAID THAT HE COULD NOT STICK THE TANK BECAUSE OF ANGLES IN THE FILLING TUBE. I TOLD HIM I WOULD RECOMMEND THAT THEY DIG TO THE TOP OF THE TANK AND PUT A STRAIGHT DROP TUBE IN SO THEY WOULD BE ABLE TO STICK THE TANK IN ORDER TO PREVENT ANOTHER SUCH INCIDENT.
WHILE DRIVER WAS FILLING TANK OIL CAME OUT OF VENT WE SENT MICHLINE UP TO CORRECT PROBLEM VENT WAS STACKED TANK WAS FILLED THE DAY BEFORE.

column168: ON 10-28-95 HAZMAT SORTER, ROBYN RAINEY REPORTED A SHIPMENT THAT WAS EMITTING AN ODOR.  I, MICHAEL A. FRYE, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TECHNICIAN, RANDY WILLIAMS RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL ON THE SCENE THE FIBERBOARD BOX WAS ISOLATED.  TECHNICIAN WILLIAMS DONNED AN ORGANIC VAPOR CARTRIDGE RESPIRATOR TO INVESTIGATE THE INNER CONTENTS. INSIDE THERE WERE FOUR GLASS RECEPTACLES WITH SCREW TYPE CLOSURES. ON 10-30-95 HAZARDOUS SORT LEAD, RHONDA CLONCH REPORTED A SHIPMENT LEAKING AT THE HAZMAT SORT FACILITY AT ABX AIR, INC.  I, MICHAEL A. FRYE, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR AND HAZARDOUS TECHNICIAN, JEFF MCLAUGHLIN RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL THIS SHIPMENT WAS SETTING ON THE MATERIAL HANDLING EQUIPMENT. INSIDE HE FOUND A 4 LITER CAPACITY GLASS RECEPTACLE.  THE MIDDLE OF THE GLASS RECEPTACLE WAS SHATTERED.  THE ENTIRE CONTENTS LEAKED OUT OF THE FIBERBOARD ONTO THE FLOOR.  THIS GLASS RECEPTACLE WAS SURROUNDED BY AN ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANIED.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND FORWARDED BACK TO THE SHIPPER.

AT APPROXIMATELY 1545 HOURS ON OCTOBER 11, A CAR INSPECTOR HEARD TANK CAR CELX 23288 VENTING FOR NO APPARENT REASON; HE REPORTED SAME TO THE TRAINMASTER.  AN EMPLOYEE INVESITGATED AND FOUND THE B END SAFETY RELIEF VALVE VENTING.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND CONRAIL'S T.  DAVIS DONNED PROTECTIVE GEAR AND INSPECTED THE CAR, TAKING LEL READINGS AS THEY WENT. THE METER READ 2% AT THE RELIEF VALVE AND A SLIGHT HISSING WAS HEARD COMING FROM THE VALVE.  MR. DAVIS CONTACTED FRA HAZMAT INSPECTOR T. GILMORE AND REQUESTED HIS PRESENCE AT THE YARD.  AFTER MR. GILMORE ARRIVED, WAS NNRIEFED, AND LEARNED THAT MR. WONNELL FROM REILY HAD A CREW READY TO UNLOAD THE CAR, HE GAVE CR PERMISSION TO MOVE THE CAR INTO REILLY INDUSTRIES.  THE CAR WAS DELIVERED AT 0145 HOURS ON THE 12TH.  THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE WAS REMOVED FROM THE CAR AND HOECHST CELANESE TOOK THE VALVE BACK TO TEXAS FOR INVESTIGATION AND TESTING.

column168: ON 28 OCTOBER, 1995 AT APPROXIMATELY 0515, A BULK CHEMICAL TANKER DRIVER BY THOMAS BILLINGS WAS TRAVELLING SOUTHBOUND ON INTERSTATE 95 IN VIRGINIA TOWARDS IT'S FINAL DESTINATION OF HOPEWELL, VA.  AT THE ABOVE MENTIONED TIME, THE DRIVER FELL AND WENT OFF THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE ROAD, THROUGH A SMALL WIRE GUARDRAIL AND INTO A RAVINE APPROXIMATELY 20 FEET DEEP.  THE EXACT LOCATION OF THE ACCIDENT WAS MILEMARKET 137 IN STAFFORD COUNTY.  THE VEHICLE ROLLED OVER APPROXIMATELY ONE AND A HALF TIMES AND LANDED ON IT'S RIGHT SIDE.  THE DRIVER WAS UNINJURED AND WAS ABLE TO EXTRACT HIMSELF FROM THE TANKER.  AS STATED IN THE REPORT, THERE WAS A LOSS OF APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF PRODUCT.  THIS WAS DUE TO AIR PRESSURE VALVE ON THE TOP OF THE TANKER BREAKING OFF.  THERE WAS NO OTHER BREACH IN THE TANKER.  AN OFF-DUTY VOLUNTEER FIRE FIGHTER WHO WAS FOLLOWING BEHIND THE TANKER AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT RADIOED FOR HELP.  COUNTY AND STATE EMERGENCY SERVICES RESPONDED TO SCENE.  AN ENVIRONMENTAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE SERVICE (INDUSTRIAL MARINE SERVICE) WAS CONTRACTED TO EVACUATE THE PRODUCT FROM THE TANKER AND REMOVE ANDY CONTAMINATED SOIL.  A SUBSEQUENT INVESTIGATION BY D.O.T. OF REGIONAL ENTERPRISE'S RESULTED IN NO PROCEDURE VIOLATIONS. THIS ACCIDENT WAS ATTRIBUTED TO DRIVER ERROR.  THE DRIVER WAS CHARGED WITH RECKLESS DRIVING AND HAS A COURT DATE OF 5 DEC. 1995.
